{
  "id": "019d3408-f677-7751-bb27-c613aff32b8d",
  "content": "# Buffered Access Tracking -- Decision Record (2026-03-28)\n\n## What: Replaced LiteStore's direct Redb writes in record_access() with DashMap buffer + periodic flush, reducing per-access cost from ~1-5ms to ~50-200ns.\n\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. DashMap inside LiteStore, QueryableStore trait unchanged, PostgresStore unaffected\n2. Dual flush triggers: 60s time-based OR 256 entries size-based\n3. No background tokio task. Opportunistic flush on record_access() calls\n4. AtomicBool CAS for single-writer flush exclusion, spin-wait in flush_sync\n5. Lossy under pressure: drop events when buffer full + flush in progress\n6. Re-insert entries into DashMap on commit failure (prevents silent data loss)\n7. Atomic per-key DashMap::remove drain (not two-phase iter+remove) to prevent race with concurrent record() calls\n\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- Two-phase iter+remove on DashMap is NOT atomic. Concurrent inserts between collect and remove are silently lost. Always use remove-during-collect pattern.\n- flush_sync must acquire the same flushing lock as try_flush, even when \"only called from Drop\". Public methods can be called from anywhere.\n- Atomic variables that gate decision boundaries need Acquire/Release ordering, not Relaxed. Relaxed is only for counters/metrics.\n- Access buffer returns success_count (entries actually written to Redb), not batch size.\n\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Existing test test_access_tracking_increments_on_retrieval assumed immediate Redb persistence. Needed flush_access_buffer() after the sleep.\n- flush_inner's full serde round-trip per entry is the real bottleneck (not the DashMap). A separate access stats Redb table would eliminate this, but deferred for now.\n\nPR: chunzhe10/corvia#TBD",
  "source_version": "mcp",
